# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xslt-transform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A **document type definition** (**DTD**) is a specification file that contains a set of *markup declarations* that define a *document type* for an SGML-family markup language (GML, SGML, XML, HTML).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The DTD specification file can be used to validate documents.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A DTD defines the valid building blocks of an XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] It defines the document structure with a list of validated elements and attributes.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A DTD can be declared inline inside an XML document, or as an external reference.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] DTDs persist in applications that need special publishing characters, such as the XML and HTML Character Entity References, which derive from larger sets defined as part of the ISO SGML standard effort.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] An attempt to create namespace-aware DTDs was being developed as Part 9 of ISO DSDL, but this was ultimately withdrawn.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] As of 2009, newer XML namespace-aware schema languages (such as W3C XML Schema and ISO RELAX NG) have largely superseded DTDs as a better way to validate XML structure.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A DTD is associated with an XML or SGML document by means of a document type declaration (DOCTYPE).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The DOCTYPE appears in the syntactic fragment *doctypedecl* near the start of an XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The declaration establishes that the document is an instance of the type defined by the referenced DTD.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The declarations in the internal subset form part of the DOCTYPE in the document itself.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The declarations in the external subset are located in a separate text file.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The external subset may be referenced via a *public identifier* and/or a *system identifier*.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Programs for reading documents may not be required to read the external subset.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However, such documents are still fully parsable in the *non*-standalone mode of validating parsers, which signals an error if it can not locate these external entities with their specified *public identifier* (FPI) or *system identifier* (a URI), or are inaccessible.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Non-validating parsers *may* eventually attempt to locate these external entities in the *non*-standalone mode (by partially interpreting the DTD only to resolve their declared parsable entities), but do not validate the content model of these documents.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] All HTML 4.01 documents conform to one of three SGML DTDs.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The system identifiers of these DTDs, if present in the DOCTYPE, are URI references.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A system identifier usually points to a specific set of declarations in a resolvable location.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] SGML allows mapping public identifiers to system identifiers in catalogs that are optionally available to the URI resolvers used by document parsing software.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] This DOCTYPE can only appear *after* the optional XML declaration, and before the document body, if the document syntax conforms to XML.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] DTDs describe the structure of a class of documents via element and attribute-list declarations.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Element declarations name the allowable set of elements within the document, and specify whether and how declared elements and runs of character data may be contained within each element.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Attribute-list declarations name the allowable set of attributes for each declared element, including the type of each attribute value, if not an explicit set of valid values.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] DTD markup declarations declare which element types, attribute lists, entities, and notations are allowed in the structure of the corresponding class of XML documents.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] An element type declaration defines an element and its possible content.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A valid XML document contains only elements that are defined in the DTD.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Element type declarations are ignored by *non-validating* SGML and XML parsers (in which cases, any elements are accepted in any order, and in any number of occurrences in the parsed document), but these declarations are still checked for form and validity.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] An attribute list specifies for a given element type the list of all possible attribute associated with that type.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] " with this type, without needing any declaration in the DTD, so the uniqueness constraint also applies to these defined identifiers when they are specified anywhere in a XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] " pipe character) of notation names, where each notation name in the enumeration must also be declared in the document type declaration; this type is not supported in HTML parsers, but is valid in SGML and XML 1.0 or 1.1 (including XHTML and SVG).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A default value can define whether an attribute must occur (`#REQUIRED`) or not (`#IMPLIED`), or whether it has a fixed value (`#FIXED`), or which value should be used as a default value ("…") in case the given attribute is left out in an XML tag.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Attribute list declarations are ignored by *non-validating* SGML and XML parsers (in which cases any attribute is accepted within all elements of the parsed document), but these declarations are still checked for well-formedness and validity.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The entity declaration assigns it a value that is retained throughout the document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A common use is to have a name more recognizable than a numeric character reference for an unfamiliar character.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Entities help to improve legibility of an XML text.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] In general, there are two types: internal and external.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Reference to the "author" internal entity is not substituted in the replacement text of the "signature" internal entity.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The "%" character for introducing parameter entity references in the DTD loses its special role outside the DTD and it becomes a literal character.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However, the references to predefined character entities are substituted wherever they occur, without needing a validating parser (they are only introduced by the "&" character).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] They provide a complete reference to unparsed external entities whose interpretation is left to the application (which interprets them directly or retrieves the external entity themselves), by assigning them a simple name, which is usable in the body of the document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] For example, notations may be used to reference non-XML data in an XML 1.1 document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] This declares the Media Type of external images with this type, and associates it with a notation name "type-image-svg".
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The declared notation name must be unique within all the document type declaration, i.e. in the external subset as well as the internal subset, at least for conformance with XML.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Notations can be associated to unparsed external entities included in the body of the SGML or XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The `PUBLIC` or `SYSTEM` parameter of these external entities specifies the FPI and/or the URI where the unparsed data of the external entity is located, and the additional `NDATA` parameter of these defined entities specifies the additional notation (i.e., effectively the MIME type here).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Notations may also be associated directly to elements as additional meta-data, without associating them to another external entity, by giving their names as possible values of some additional attributes (also declared in the DTD within the `<!ATTLIST ...>` declaration of the element).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The example above shows a notation named "type-image-svg" that references the standard public FPI and the system identifier (the standard URI) of an SVG 1.1 document, instead of specifying just a system identifier as in the first example (which was a relative URI interpreted locally as a MIME type).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] This annotation is referenced directly within the unparsed "type" attribute of the "img" element, but its content is not retrieved.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] It also declares another notation for a vendor-specific application, to annotate the "sgml" root element in the document.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] In both cases, the declared notation named is used directly in a declared "type" attribute, whose content is specified in the DTD with the "NOTATION" attribute type (this "type" attribute is declared for the "sgml" element, as well as for the "img" element).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However, the "title" attribute of the "img" element specifies the internal entity "example1SVGTitle" whose declaration that does not define an annotation, so it is parsed by validating parsers and the entity replacement text is "Title of example1.svg".
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The effective content for the "img" element be the content of this second external resource.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Only one notation name may be specified in the value of ENTITY attributes (there is no support in SGML, XML 1.0 or XML 1.1 for multiple notation names in the same declared external ENTITY, so separate attributes are needed).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However multiple external entities may be referenced (in a space-separated list of names) in attributes declared with type ENTITIES, and where each named external entity is also declared with its own notation).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Notations are also completely opaque for XML and SGML parsers, so they are not differentiated by the type of the external entity that they may reference (for these parsers they just have a unique name associated to a public identifier (an FPI) and/or a system identifier (a URI)).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Some applications (but not XML or SGML parsers themselves) also allow referencing notations indirectly by naming them in the `"URN:''name''"` value of a standard CDATA attribute, everywhere a URI can be specified.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However this behaviour is application-specific, and requires that the application maintains a catalog of known URNs to resolve them into the notations that have been parsed in a standard SGML or XML parser.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] This use allows notations to be defined only in a DTD stored as an external entity and referenced only as the external subset of documents, and allows these documents to remain compatible with validating XML or SGML parsers that have no direct support for notations.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Even in validating SGML or XML 1.0 or XML 1.1 parsers, the external entities referenced by an FPI and/or URI in declared notations are not retrieved automatically by the parsers themselves.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The XML DTD syntax is one of several XML schema languages.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However, many of the schema languages do not fully replace the XML DTD.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] Most XML schema languages are only replacements for element declarations and attribute list declarations, in such a way that it becomes possible to parse XML documents with *non-validating* XML parsers (if the only purpose of the external DTD subset was to define the schema).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] A *non-validating* parser may, however, elect not to read parsable *external entities* (including the *external subset*), and does not have to honor the content model restrictions defined in element declarations and in attribute list declarations.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] If the XML document depends on parsable external entities (including the specified *external subset*, or parsable external entities declared in the *internal subset*), it should assert `standalone="no"` in its XML declaration.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The validating DTD may be identified by using XML Catalogs to retrieve its specified *external subset*.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] If it just includes any PUBLIC identifier, it *may* be processed as standalone, if the XML processor knows this PUBLIC identifier in its local catalog from where it can retrieve an associated DTD entity.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] `person` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains one element named `name`, followed by one named `birthdate` (optional), then `gender` (also optional) and `socialsecuritynumber` (also optional).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The `?` indicates that an element is optional.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The reference to the `name` element name has no `?`, so a `person` element *must* contain a `name` element.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] `name` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains "parsed character data" (#PCDATA).
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] `birthdate` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] `gender` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] `socialsecuritynumber` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] An example of an XML file that uses and conforms to this DTD follows.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The DTD is referenced here as an external subset, via the SYSTEM specifier and a URI.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] One can render this in an XML-enabled browser (such as Internet Explorer or Mozilla Firefox) by pasting and saving the DTD component above to a text file named *example.dtd* and the XML file to a differently-named text file, and opening the XML file with the browser.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] The files should both be saved in the same directory.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] However, many browsers do not check that an XML document confirms to the rules in the DTD; they are only required to check that the DTD is syntactically correct.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] For security reasons, they may also choose not to read the external DTD.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] An XML DTD can be used to create a Denial-of-service attack by defining nested entities that expand exponentially, or by sending the XML parser to an external resource that never returns.
[src:xslt-transform/document-type-definition] For this reason, .NET Framework provides a property that allows prohibiting or skipping DTD parsing, and recent versions of Microsoft Office applications (Microsoft Office 2010 and higher) refuse to open XML files that contain DTD declarations.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:xslt-transform/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
