[src:xslt-transform/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:xslt-transform/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The XPath language is based on a tree representation of the XML document, and provides the ability to navigate around the tree, selecting nodes by a variety of criteria.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] In popular use (though not in the official specification), an XPath expression is often referred to simply as "an XPath".
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Originally motivated by a desire to provide a common syntax and behavior model between XPointer and XSLT, subsets of the XPath query language are used in other W3C specifications such as XML Schema, XForms and the Internationalization Tag Set (ITS).
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] XPath has been adopted by a number of XML processing libraries and tools, many of which also offer CSS Selectors, another W3C standard, as a simpler alternative to XPath.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] There are several versions of XPath in use.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] However, XPath 1.0 is still the version that is most widely available.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The most important kind of expression in XPath is a *location path*.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] A location path consists of a sequence of *location steps*.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] An XPath expression is evaluated with respect to a *context node*.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] An Axis Specifier such as 'child' or 'descendant' specifies the direction to navigate from the context node.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The node test and the predicate are used to filter the nodes specified by the axis specifier: For example, the node test 'A' requires that all nodes navigated to must have label 'A'.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] A predicate can be used to specify that the selected nodes have certain properties, which are specified by XPath expressions themselves.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The XPath syntax comes in two flavors: the *abbreviated syntax*, is more compact and allows XPaths to be written and read easily using intuitive and, in many cases, familiar characters and constructs.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The *full syntax* is more verbose, but allows for more options to be specified, and is more descriptive if read carefully.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The compact notation allows many defaults and abbreviations for common cases.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] that selects C elements that are children of B elements that are children of the A element that forms the outermost element of the XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The XPath syntax is designed to mimic URI (Uniform Resource Identifier) and Unix-style file path syntax.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] More complex expressions can be constructed by specifying an axis other than the default 'child' axis, a node test other than a simple name, or predicates, which can be written in square brackets after any step.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] selects the first child ('`*[1]`'), whatever its name, of every B element that itself is a child or other, deeper descendant ('`//`') of an A element that is a child of the current context node (the expression does not begin with a '`/`').
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The predicate `[1]` binds more tightly than the `/` operator.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] To select the first node selected by the expression `A//B/*`, write `(A//B/*)[1]`.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Note also, index values in XPath predicates (technically, 'proximity positions' of XPath node sets) start from 1, not 0 as common in languages like C and Java.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Here, in each step of the XPath, the **axis** (e.g.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] `child` or `descendant-or-self`) is explicitly specified, followed by `::` and then the **node test**, such as `A` or `node()` in the examples above.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Axis specifiers indicate navigation direction within the tree representation of the XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] As an example of using the **attribute** axis in abbreviated syntax, `//a/@href` selects the attribute called `href` in `a` elements anywhere in the document tree.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The expression **.** (an abbreviation for **self::node()**) is most commonly used within a predicate to refer to the currently selected node.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] For example, `h3[.='See also']` selects an element called `h3` in the current context, whose text content is `See also`.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Node tests may consist of specific node names or more general expressions.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] In the case of an XML document in which the namespace prefix `gs` has been defined, `//gs:enquiry` will find all the `enquiry` elements in that namespace, and `//gs:*` will find all elements, regardless of local name, in that namespace.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Predicates, written as expressions in square brackets, can be used to filter a node-set according to some condition.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] For example, `a` returns a node-set (all the `a` elements which are children of the context node), and `a[@href='help.php']` keeps only those elements having an `href` attribute with the value `help.php`.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] There is no limit to the number of predicates in a step, and they need not be confined to the last step in an XPath.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Paths specified in predicates begin at the context of the current step (i.e. that of the immediately preceding node test) and do not alter that context.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] All predicates must be satisfied for a match to occur.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] When the value of the predicate is numeric, it is syntactic-sugar for comparing against the node's position in the node-set (as given by the function `position()`).
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] So `p[1]` is shorthand for `p[position()=1]` and selects the first `p` element child, while `p[last()]` is shorthand for `p[position()=last()]` and selects the last `p` child of the context node.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] In other cases, the value of the predicate is automatically converted to a Boolean.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] When the predicate evaluates to a node-set, the result is true when the node-set is non-empty.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Thus `p[@x]` selects those `p` elements that have an attribute named `x`.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The reference to an attribute of the top-level element in the first predicate affects neither the context of other predicates nor that of the location step itself.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Predicate order is significant if predicates test the position of a node.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Each predicate takes a node-set returns a (potentially) smaller node-set.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] So `a[1][@href='help.php']` will find a match only if the first `a` child of the context node satisfies the condition `@href='help.php'`, while `a[@href='help.php'][1]` will find the first `a` child that satisfies this condition.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] XPath 1.0 defines four data types: node-sets (sets of nodes with no intrinsic order), strings, numbers and Booleans.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Some of the more commonly useful functions are detailed below.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] returns a number representing the position of this node in the sequence of nodes currently being processed (for example, the nodes selected by an xsl:for-each instruction in XSLT).
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] returns the number of nodes in the node-set supplied as its argument.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] converts any of the four XPath data types into a string according to built-in rules.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] If the value of the argument is a node-set, the function returns the string-value of the first node in document order, ignoring any further nodes.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] is removed and any sequences of whitespace characters are replaced by a single space.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] formatted, which could make further string processing unreliable.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] converts the string values of all the nodes found by the XPath argument into numbers, according to the built-in casting rules, then returns the sum of these numbers.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Expressions can be created inside predicates using the operators: `=, !=, <=, <, >=` and `>`.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Boolean expressions may be combined with brackets `()` and the Boolean operators `and` and `or` as well as the `not()` function described above.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Numeric calculations can use `*, +, -, div` and `mod`.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Strings can consist of any Unicode characters.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] `//item[@price > 2*@discount]` selects items whose price attribute is greater than twice the numeric value of their discount attribute.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Entire node-sets can be combined ('unioned') using the vertical bar character |.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Node sets that meet one or more of several conditions can be found by combining the conditions inside a predicate with '`or`'.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] `v[x or y] | w[z]` will return a single node-set consisting of all the `v` elements that have `x` or `y` child-elements, as well as all the `w` elements that have `z` child-elements, that were found in the current context.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] selects addresses of all English Wikimedia projects (text of all `edition` elements where `language` attribute is equal to *English*).
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] selects addresses of all Wikipedias (text of all `edition` elements that exist under `project` element with a name attribute of *Wikipedia*).
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] The Java package **`javax.xml.xpath`** has been part of Java standard edition since Java 5 via the Java API for XML Processing.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] Technically this is an XPath API rather than an XPath implementation, and it allows the programmer the ability to select a specific implementation that conforms to the interface.
[src:xslt-transform/xpath] XPath is increasingly used to express constraints in schema languages for XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The language was developed by the XML Query working group of the W3C, with version 1.0 becoming a W3C Recommendation in January 2007.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery development is closely coordinated with the development of XSLT by the XSL Working Group.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Both groups jointly maintain XPath, a shared component of XQuery and XSLT.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery extends XPath with features like FLWOR (For, Let, Where, Order by, Return) expressions, making it semantically similar to SQL but optimized for hierarchical rather than relational data.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery 3.1, published in March 2017, added support for JSON and introduced maps, arrays, and additional higher-order functions, significantly expanding the language's capabilities for modern data processing.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery is implemented by many database systems, XML databases, and XML processors, including BaseX, eXist, MarkLogic, Saxon, and Berkeley DB XML, making it a cornerstone technology for processing XML data in enterprise software applications.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery provides the means to extract and manipulate data from XML documents or any data source that can be viewed as XML, such as relational databases or office documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery contains a superset of XPath expression syntax to address specific parts of an XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] It supplements this with a SQL-like "FLWOR expression" for performing joins.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] A FLWOR expression is constructed from the five clauses after which it is named: FOR, LET, WHERE, ORDER BY, RETURN.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The language also provides syntax allowing new XML documents to be constructed.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Where the element and attribute names are known in advance, an XML-like syntax can be used; in other cases, expressions referred to as dynamic node constructors are available.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] All these constructs are defined as expressions within the language, and can be arbitrarily nested.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The language is based on the XQuery and XPath Data Model (XDM) which uses a tree-structured model of the information content of an XML document, containing seven kinds of nodes: document nodes, elements, attributes, text nodes, comments, processing instructions, and namespaces.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XDM also models all values as sequences (a singleton value is considered to be a sequence of length one).
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The items in a sequence can either be XML nodes or atomic values.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Atomic values may be integers, strings, Booleans, and so on: the full list of types is based on the primitive types defined in XML Schema.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Features for updating XML documents or databases, and full text search capability, are not part of the core language, but are defined in add-on extension standards: XQuery Update Facility 1.0 supports update feature and XQuery and XPath Full Text 1.0 supports full text search in XML documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery 3.0 adds support for full functional programming, in that functions are values that can be manipulated (stored in variables, passed to higher-order functions, and dynamically called).
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] All XQuery constructs for performing computations are expressions.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] There are no statements, even though some of the keywords appear to suggest statement-like behaviors.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] To execute a function, the expression within the body is evaluated and its value is returned.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] This style is common in functional programming languages.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Generating summary reports on data stored in an XML database.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Searching textual documents on the Web for relevant information and compiling the results.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Selecting and transforming XML data to XHTML to be published on the Web.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Pulling data from databases to be used for the application integration.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Splitting up an XML document that represents multiple transactions into multiple XML documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Although XQuery was initially conceived as a query language for large collections of XML documents, it is also capable of transforming individual documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] As such, its capabilities overlap with XSLT, which was designed expressly to allow input XML documents to be transformed into HTML or other formats.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The XSLT 2.0 and XQuery standards were developed by separate working groups within W3C, working together to ensure a common approach where appropriate.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] They share the same data model (XDM), type system, and function library, and both include XPath 2.0 as a sublanguage.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The two languages, however, are rooted in different traditions and serve the needs of different communities.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XSLT was primarily conceived as a stylesheet language whose primary goal was to render XML for the human reader on screen, on the web (as web template language), or on paper.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery was primarily conceived as a database query language in the tradition of SQL.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Because the two languages originate in different communities, XSLT is stronger in its handling of narrative documents with more flexible structure, while XQuery is stronger in its data handling (for example, when performing relational joins).
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XSLT 1.0 appeared as a Recommendation in 1999, whereas XQuery 1.0 only became a Recommendation in early 2007; as a result, XSLT is still much more widely used.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Both languages have similar expressive power, though XSLT 2.0 has many features that are missing from XQuery 1.0, such as grouping, number and date formatting, and greater control over XML namespaces.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Many of these features were planned for XQuery 3.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Any comparison must take into account the version of XSLT.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XSLT 1.0 and XSLT 2.0 are very different languages.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XSLT 2.0, in particular, has been heavily influenced by XQuery in its move to strong typing and schema-awareness.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Usability studies have shown that XQuery is easier to learn than XSLT, especially for users with previous experience of database languages such as SQL.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] This can be attributed to the fact that XQuery is a smaller language with fewer concepts to learn, and to the fact that programs are more concise.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] It is also true that XQuery is more orthogonal, in that any expression can be used in any syntactic context.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] By contrast, XSLT is a two-language system in which XPath expressions can be nested in XSLT instructions but not vice versa.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XSLT is currently stronger than XQuery for applications that involve making small changes to a document (for example, deleting all the NOTE elements).
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Such applications are generally handled in XSLT by use of a coding pattern that involves an identity template that copies all nodes unchanged, modified by specific templates that modify selected nodes.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery has no equivalent to this coding pattern, though in future versions it will be possible to tackle such problems using the update facilities in the language that are under development.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery 1.0 lacked any kind of mechanism for dynamic binding or polymorphism; this has been remedied with the introduction of functions as first-class values in XQuery 3.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The absence of this capability starts to become noticeable when writing large applications, or when writing code that is designed to be reusable in different environments.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XSLT offers two complementary mechanisms in this area: the dynamic matching of template rules, and the ability to override rules using `xsl:import`, that make it possible to write applications with multiple customization layers.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The absence of these facilities from XQuery 1.0 was a deliberate design decision: it has the consequence that XQuery is very amenable to static analysis, which is essential to achieve the level of optimization needed in database query languages.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] This also makes it easier to detect errors in XQuery code at compile time.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The fact that XSLT 2.0 uses XML syntax makes it rather verbose in comparison to XQuery 1.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] However, many large applications take advantage of this capability by using XSLT to read, write, or modify stylesheets dynamically as part of a processing pipeline.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The use of XML syntax also enables the use of XML-based tools for managing XSLT code.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] By contrast, XQuery syntax is more suitable for embedding in traditional programming languages such as Java (see XQuery API for Java) or C#.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] If necessary, XQuery code can also be expressed in an XML syntax called XQueryX.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The XQueryX representation of XQuery code is rather verbose and not convenient for humans, but can easily be processed with XML tools, for example transformed with XSLT stylesheets.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Both became W3C Recommendations as extensions to XQuery 1.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] Efforts to adapt them for XQuery 3.0 were abandoned due to resource constraints.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] A scripting (procedural) extension for XQuery was proposed but never completed.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The EXPath Community Group develops extensions for XQuery and related standards (XPath, XSLT, XProc, and XForms).
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] JSONiq is an extension of XQuery that adds support to extract and transform data from JSON documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] It is published under the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 3.0 license.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] XQuery 3.1 de facto deprecates JSONiq as it has added full support for JSON.
[src:xslt-transform/xquery] The EXQuery project develops standards around creating portable XQuery applications.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO is considered feature complete by W3C: the last update for the Working Draft was in January 2012, and its Working Group closed in November 2013.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Unlike the combination of HTML and CSS, XSL-FO is a unified presentational language.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] It has no semantic markup as this term is used in HTML.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] And, unlike CSS which modifies the default presentation of an external XML or HTML document, it stores all of the document's data within itself.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The general idea behind XSL-FO's use is that the user writes a document, not in FO, but in an XML language.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XHTML, DocBook, and TEI are all possible examples.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Then, the user obtains an XSLT transform, either by writing one themselves or by finding one for the document type in question.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This XSLT transform converts the XML into XSL-FO.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Once the XSL-FO document is generated, it is then passed to an application called an FO processor.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] FO processors convert the XSL-FO document into something that is readable, printable or both.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The most common output of XSL-FO is a PDF file or as PostScript, but some FO processors can output to other formats like RTF files or even just a window in the user's GUI displaying the sequence of pages and their contents.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The XSLT language itself was originally conceived only for this purpose; it is now in widespread use for more general XML transformations.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This transformation step is taken so much for granted in XSL-FO that it is not uncommon for people to call the XSLT that turns XML into XSL-FO the actual XSL-FO document itself.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Even tutorials on XSL-FO tend to be written with XSLT commands around the FO processing instructions.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The XSLT transformation step is exceptionally powerful.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] It allows for the automatic generation of a table of contents, linked references, an index, and various other possibilities.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] An XSL-FO document is not like a PDF or a PostScript document.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] It does not definitively describe the layout of the text on various pages.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Instead, it describes what the pages look like and where the various contents go.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] From there, an FO processor determines how to position the text within the boundaries described by the FO document.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The XSL-FO specification even allows different FO processors to have varying responses with regard to the resultant generated pages.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] For example, some FO processors can hyphenate words to minimize space when breaking a line, while others choose not to.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Different processors may even use different hyphenation algorithms, ranging from very simple to more complex hyphenation algorithms that take into account whether the previous or next line also is hyphenated.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] These will change, in some borderline cases quite substantially, the layout of the various pages.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] There are other cases where the XSL-FO specification explicitly allows FO processors some degree of choice with regard to layout.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This differentiation between FO processors, creating inconsistent results between processors is often not a concern.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This is because the general purpose behind XSL-FO is to generate paged, printed media.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO documents themselves are usually used as intermediaries, mostly to generate either PDF files or a printed document as the final form to be distributed.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This is as opposed to how HTML is generated and distributed as a final form directly to the user.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The XSL-FO language was designed for paged media; as such, the concept of pages is an integral part of XSL-FO's structure.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] FO works best for what could be called "content-driven" design.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This is the standard method of layout for books, articles, legal documents, and so forth.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] It involves a single flowing span of fairly contiguous text, with various repeating information built into the margins of a page.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] This is as opposed to "layout-driven" design, which is used in newspapers or magazines.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] If content in those documents does not fit in the required space, some of it is trimmed away until it does fit.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO does not easily handle the tight restrictions of magazine layout; indeed, in many cases, it lacks the ability to express some forms of said layout.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Despite the basic nature of the language's design, it is capable of a great deal of expressiveness.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Tables, lists, side floats, and a variety of other features are available.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] These features are comparable to CSS's layout features, though some of those features are expected to be built by the XSLT.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO documents are XML documents, but they do not have to conform to any DTD or schema.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Instead, they conform to a syntax defined in the XSL-FO specification.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO documents contain two required sections.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The first section details a list of named page layouts.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The second section is a list of document data, with markup, that uses the various page layouts to determine how the content fills the various pages.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Page layouts define the properties of the page.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] They can define the directions for the flow of text, so as to match the conventions for the language in question.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] They define the size of a page as well as the margins of that page.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] More importantly, they can define sequences of pages that allow for effects where the odd and even pages look different.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] For example, one can define a page layout sequence that gives extra space to the inner margins for printing purposes; this allows more space to be given to the margin where the book will be bound.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The document data portion is broken up into a sequence of flows, where each flow is attached to a page layout.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The flows contain a list of blocks which, in turn, each contain a list of text data, inline markup elements, or a combination of the two.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Content may also be added to the margins of the document, for page numbers, chapter headings and the like.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Blocks and inline elements function in much the same way as for CSS, though some of the rules for padding and margins differ between FO and CSS.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The direction, relative to the page orientation, for the progression of blocks and inlines can be fully specified, thus allowing FO documents to function under languages that are read different from English.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The language of the FO specification, unlike that of CSS 2.1, uses direction-neutral terms like start and end rather than left and right when describing these directions.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO's basic content markup is derived from CSS and its cascading rules.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] As such, many attributes in XSL-FO propagate into the child elements unless explicitly overridden.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] XSL-FO is capable of a great deal of textual layout functionality.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] In addition to the information as specified above, XSL-FO's language allows for the specification of the following.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] A page can be defined to have multiple columns.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] When this is the case, blocks flow from one column into the next by default.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Individual blocks can be set to span all columns, creating a textual break in the page.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The columns above this break will flow into each other, as will the columns below the break.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] But no text is allowed to flow from the above section to the below section.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Because of the nature of XSL-FO's page specification, multiple pages may actually have different numbers and widths of columns.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] As such, text can flow from a 3 column page to a 5 column page to a 1 column page quite easily.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] All FO features work within the restrictions of a multi-column page.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] We can span multiple columns by specifying two attributes i.e.,. span, padding-after .
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] An XSL-FO list is, essentially, two sets of blocks stacked side by side.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] An entry consists of a block on the "left", or start inline direction, and a block sequence on the "right", or end inline direction.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The block on the left is conceptually what would be the number or bullet in a list.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] However, it could just as easily be a string of text, as one might see in a glossary entry.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The block on the right works as expected.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Both of these blocks can be block containers, or have multiple blocks in a single list entry.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Numbering of XSL-FO lists, when they are numbered, is expected to be done by the XSLT, or whatever other process, that generated the XSL-FO document.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] As such, number lists are to be explicitly numbered in XSL-FO.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The user can specify Widow and Orphan for blocks or for the flow itself, and allow the attributes to cascade into child blocks.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] Additionally, blocks can be specified to be kept together on a single page.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] For example, an image block and the description of that image can be set to never be separated.
[src:xslt-transform/xsl-formatting-objects] The FO processor will do its best to adhere to these commands, even if it requires creating a great deal of empty space on a page.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT 3.0 implementations support Java, .NET, C/C++, Python, PHP and NodeJS.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] An XSLT 3.0 JavaScript library can also be hosted within the web browser.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Modern web browsers also include native support for XSLT 1.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT has become obsolete in the browser due to better technologies.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Google Chrome will remove its XSLT implementation to make the browser more secure.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] The XSLT document transformation specifies how to transform an XML document into new document (usually XML, but other formats, such as plain text are supported).
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Typically, input documents are XML files, but anything from which the processor can build an XQuery and XPath Data Model can be used, such as relational database tables or geographical information systems.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] While XSLT was originally designed as a special-purpose language for XML transformation, the language is Turing-complete, making it theoretically capable of arbitrary computations.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT is influenced by functional languages, and by text-based pattern matching languages like SNOBOL and AWK.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Its most direct predecessor is DSSSL, which did for SGML what XSLT does for XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] The XSLT processor takes one or more XML source documents, plus one or more XSLT stylesheets, and processes them to produce one or multiple output documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In contrast to widely implemented imperative programming languages like C, XSLT is declarative.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] The basic processing paradigm is pattern matching.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] First, assuming a stylesheet has already been read and prepared, the processor builds a source tree from the input XML document.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] It then processes the source tree's root node, finds the best-matching template for that node in the stylesheet, and evaluates the template's contents.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Instructions in each template generally direct the processor to either create nodes in the result tree, or to process more nodes in the source tree in the same way as the root node.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Finally the result tree is serialized as XML or HTML text.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT uses XPath to identify subsets of the source document tree and perform calculations.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XPath also provides a range of functions, which XSLT itself further augments.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT 1.0 uses XPath 1.0, while XSLT 2.0 uses XPath 2.0.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT 3.0 will work with either XPath 3.0 or 3.1.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In the case of 1.0 and 2.0, the XSLT and XPath specifications were published on the same date.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] With 3.0, however, they were no longer synchronized; XPath 3.0 became a Recommendation in April 2014, followed by XPath 3.1 in February 2017; XSLT 3.0 followed in June 2017.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT functionalities overlap with those of XQuery, which was initially conceived as a query language for large collections of XML documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] The XSLT 2.0 and XQuery 1.0 standards were developed by separate working groups within W3C, working together to ensure a common approach where appropriate.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] They share the same data model, type system, and function library, and both include XPath 2.0 as a sublanguage.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] XSLT was primarily conceived as a stylesheet language whose primary goal was to render XML for the human reader on screen, on the web (as a web template language), or on paper.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Because the two languages originate in different communities, XSLT is stronger in its handling of narrative documents with more flexible structure, while XQuery is stronger in its data handling, for example when performing relational joins.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] The `<output>` element can optionally take the attribute `media-type`, which allows one to set the media type (or MIME type) for the resulting output, for example: `<xsl:output output="xml" media-type="application/xml"/>`.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] The XSLT 1.0 recommendation recommends the more general attribute types `text/xml` and `application/xml` since for a long time there was no registered media type for XSLT.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] During this time `text/xsl` became the de facto standard.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In XSLT 1.0 it was not specified how the `media-type` values should be used.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] With the release of the XSLT 2.0, the W3C recommended in 2007 the registration of the MIME media type `application/xslt+xml` and it was later registered with the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Pre-1.0 working drafts of XSLT used `text/xsl` in their embedding examples, and this type was implemented and continued to be promoted by Microsoft in Internet Explorer and MSXML circa 2012.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] It is also widely recognized in the `xml-stylesheet` processing instruction by other browsers.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In practice, therefore, users wanting to control transformation in the browser using this processing instruction were obliged to use this unregistered media type.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] This XHTML generates the output below when rendered in a web browser.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In order for a web browser to be able to apply an XSL transformation to an XML document on display, an XML stylesheet processing instruction can be inserted into XML.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In this example, `text/xsl` is technically incorrect according to the W3C specifications (which say the type should be `application/xslt+xml`), but it is the only media type that is widely supported across browsers as of 2009, and the situation is unchanged in 2021.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Most early XSLT processors were interpreters.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] More recently, code generation is increasingly common, using portable intermediate languages (such as Java bytecode or .NET Common Intermediate Language) as the target.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] However, even the interpretive products generally offer separate analysis and execution phases, allowing an optimized expression tree to be created in memory and reused to perform multiple transformations.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] This gives substantial performance benefits in online publishing applications, where the same transformation is applied many times per second to different source documents.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] This separation is reflected in the design of XSLT processing APIs (such as JAXP).
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Early XSLT processors had very few optimizations.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Stylesheet documents were read into Document Object Models and the processor would act on them directly.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] Many processors also use tree representations that are significantly more efficient (in both space and time) than general-purpose DOM implementations.
[src:xslt-transform/xslt] In June 2014, Debbie Lockett and Michael Kay introduced an open-source benchmarking framework for XSLT processors called XT-Speedo.
